<div itemprop="articleBody">
<h1>Tutorial 40. Automatic Calculation of Adjustments to the Lace Top Pattern.</h1>
<p><strong>We can start calculating adjustments to our pattern of a lace top. </strong>As I mentioned before, it is based on my pattern of a corset with shoulders. We will use the Automatic Calculator, and namely the <strong>Table for Automatic Calculation of Adjustments to the Corset with Shoulders Pattern.</strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image001.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>Put your client’s measurements in the corresponding boxes.</strong> If the measurements taken off your mock-up differ from my given pattern measurements, you should adjust them as well in the table.</p>
<p><strong>It takes an instant to do the calculations. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Please notice the warning in the line titled “Dart Depth.” </strong>It says that only positive dart depth values are to be taken into account, while negative values are to be ignored.</p>
<p>In our particular case, we are dealing with a negative dart depth so we will not account for it in the calculations. I will demonstrate calculations with positive dart depth values in the examples to follow.</p>
<p><strong>Let us now adjust the corset with shoulders pattern. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image003.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Although we are going to use it for a lace top, I never make any additional adjustments to this pattern based on fabric elasticity. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I simply prepare it as if I were going to sew with plain non-elastic fabric. </strong>The client will just feel a lot more comfortable in a top sewn with elastic fabric, that’s all.</p>
<p><strong>Please remember that your client’s Side Length measurement must comply with the anatomy of the top, </strong>i.e. the side seam must be as tall as possible and reach as close to the armscye as it can.</p>
<p>But since we are making a top with cap-sleeves, the side seam length is not as critical <strong>in our particular case </strong>as it would be if we were making a top with short sleeves or long set-in sleeves.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I print out the table with calculated values and start applying adjustments to the pattern. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I remove 1cm along the fold line of the centre front piece.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>It follows from the calculations that the front side seam line must be shifted 0.5cm outwards. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Let me remind you again </strong>that the new side seam line should be drawn after the initial pattern which you put down with a shift to either widen or narrow the piece depending on calculations. You preserve the initial side seam length by marking the initial top and bottom points of the side edge on the new line.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The back side seam line needs to be shifted 2cm inwards in accordance with the calculations. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Again, </strong>I use the standard side back piece as a template to re-draw the back side seam line preserving its initial length.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I apply adjustments to the back princess seam lines of the side back piece and the centre back piece. </strong></p>
<p><strong>According to the calculations, I shift it 0.3cm inwards at the bust line level, 0.5cm outwards at the under-bust line level, 0.4cm inwards at the waist level, and 0.3cm inwards at the stomach level. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I re-draw the back princess seam lines accordingly.</strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>Looking at the new princess seam lines, I can tell that they are somewhat wavy but, at the same time, basically parallel to each other. </strong>The waistline dart got deeper, which shows that my client has rather pronounced curves. I do not prolong the new princess seam lines up to the very top because I will still have to work on the top parts of the back pieces.</p>
<p><strong>Now let us look at the front princess seams. </strong></p>
<p><strong>As follows from the calculations, I shift it 0.4cm inwards at the waist level and 0.3cm inwards at the stomach level. I re-draw the front princess seam lines accordingly. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>Now let us adjust the top of the front pieces. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Clip toward Armscye needs to be made 1.6cm shorter according to the calculations. I apply this adjustment to the side front piece and the centre front piece. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image024.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Bust to Shoulder needs to be increased by 1.5cm. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image026.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Bust to Shoulder Tip also needs to be increased by 1.5cm. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image028.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I connect the resulting points and re-draw the shoulder line. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image030.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>Our client’s Shoulder to Shoulder Across Front is 3cm bigger than on the pattern though. </strong>I prolong the new shoulder line by 3cm.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image032.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Then I re-draw the armscye line with regard to the adjusted Shoulder to Shoulder and Clips. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image034.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>If you have followed my recommendation and measured the distance from Centre Waist to Sternal Notch, then you should mark it up from the waistline along the fold line of the centre front piece and re-draw the neck hole. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image036.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image038.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>The centre front piece is ready! </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image040.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Next, I take the side front piece, connect the new clip point with the top point of the new side seam line, and re-draw the armscye. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Unfortunately, I made a mistake: </strong>I did not take into account that the front side seam line was shortened by 1cm as was proposed by the calculations. I will fix this mistake later and adjust the armscye line of the side front piece.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image042.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Now let us adjust the back pieces. </strong></p>
<p><strong>My client’s Centre Length Back is 5cm smaller than on the pattern. </strong>I step 5cm down the measurement line on the initial centre back piece.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image044.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Please note</strong> that the front of the top became longer than it was while the back, on the contrary, was made shorter based on the calculations. This effect points at certain individual anatomic features of our client’s body. <strong>The calculated values show</strong> that our client’s natural standing posture is with her breasts forward, her shoulders pulled back, and her back very straight. This posture results in shorter back and longer front.</p>
<p><strong>I would also like to say that all these examples are based on my actual clients’ measurements. </strong>Unfortunately, I can no longer visually remember this particular woman’s figure because it has been many years since she came to my atelier.</p>
<p>But her measurements do show me that her figure was exactly as described above.</p>
<p><strong>There is another way to check this assumption. </strong>Shoulder to Shoulder Across Front on women with such figures usually either coincides or differs very little from Shoulder to Shoulder Across Back.</p>
<p><strong>And it is true: if you look at the table, you will see that her measurements are 37cm and 36cm correspondingly. </strong>This means her shoulders are pulled back making the back itself narrower. Hence the 1cm difference between Shoulder to Shoulder Across Back and Shoulder to Shoulder Across Front.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image048.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>My client’s Shoulder Slope Back is 2cm smaller than on the pattern.</strong> I step 2cm down the measurement line of the centre back piece.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image076.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image078.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>It is also clear from the table that I need to add 0.5cm to Shoulder to Shoulder Across Back. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image080.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I draw a parallel line 2cm below the initial shoulder line and add the lacking 0.5cm. </strong>This is the outer shoulder point.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image082.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Unfortunately, I did not measure my client’s Full Length Back.</strong> If I knew it, I could draw the shoulder line more precisely by connecting the outer shoulder point with the top shoulder point.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image084.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>As I said, the new shoulder line is drawn parallel to the old one since I don’t know my client’s Full Length Back, i.e. distance from side neck point to waist. I mark 9cm from the outer shoulder point corresponding with my client’s Shoulder Length. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Make sure the front shoulder line matches the back shoulder line. </strong>We are making a top, and it does not imply any shoulder darts like in jackets or dresses.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image086.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I can draw the back neck after drawing the shoulder line. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image088.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>It follows from the calculations that Width Back needs to be made 0.5cm smaller. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image090.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I remove 0.5cm from the corresponding measurement line. </strong>Now I can safely connect the shoulder tip with the new Width Back point.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image092.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I draw a smooth princess seam line on the centre back piece.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image094.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The back side seam line is now 1cm shorter than before. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I adjust the side back piece and fix the mistake I made on the side front piece by shortening the side seam line. Then I re-draw the armscyes. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image096.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I highlight the new lines. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image098.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>And now I would like to draw your attention to the additional dart formed at the bust line level of the back princess seam on the adjusted back piece. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image100.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>You can transfer this dart to the side seams and straighten the back princess seam lines if you don’t like the shape suggested by the automatic calculations. </strong>Shifting the side seam line by 0.5cm will make no big difference for the top.</p>
<p><strong>I transfer the dart to the side seam and straighten the princess seam lines although I don’t have to. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image102.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image104.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Let me say a couple of words about the sleeves of the top. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Put a sample sleeve on the client or take a measuring tape, measure her armscye area where the cap-sleeve will be set, and mark it on her. And measure her Arm Fullness at the same time so you can cut a sleeve of the right size. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image106.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Then, take the sleeve pattern enclosed with the book and mark the required sleeve cap length along the top edge in correspondence with your client’s armscye size.</strong> You will most likely have to either overlap the sleeve pieces or make a gap between them depending on the measurement.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image108.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Next, knowing the length of your cap-sleeve, adjust the pattern to your client’s Arm Fullness by shifting the sleeve pieces against each other at an angle. </strong></p>
<p><strong>That’s it. You have a custom cap-sleeve pattern for the top. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image110.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The additional Armscye Circumference measurement taken off your client will help you double-check the adjusted pattern. </strong>This is done by measuring the armscye lines on all four pieces, summing up their lengths, and subtracting the seam allowances. The resulting value should be very close to the Armscye Circumference.</p>
<p><strong>If there is a noticeable difference between your client’s Armscye Circumference and the same measurement of the adjusted pattern, </strong>then I recommend you should double-check all measurements: Side Length, Nape to Waist, Bust to Shoulder, etc. These measurements affect the lengths of armscye lines on all pieces. Another reason could be that you measured your client’s Armscye Circumference incorrectly in the first place. Double-check it on the client.</p>
<p><strong>As for us, we are now ready for the cutting. </strong></p>
<p><strong>We have at hand an adjusted corset pattern and an adjusted top pattern. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I recommend you should first of all sew mock-up corset and top using the adjusted patterns. </strong>It will be incredibly helpful if you are a beginner in corset-making.</p>
<p><strong>By sewing mock-ups, you will be able to: </strong></p>
<p><strong>- Double-check all lengths. </strong>Beginners with insufficient experience tend to miss out some nuances when adjusting standard patterns after clients’ measurements. And this inevitably results in a difference in the lengths of princess seam lines or side seam lines.</p>
<p><strong>Of course, a difference of 1-2mm is not crucial but it does lead to certain problems. </strong>When you start assembling the garment, you will try to do something with the fabric to even out the sewing edges: for example, ease it in or stretch it in certain areas. This will inevitably lead to distortion and related defects. These defects may seem insignificant at first. But they will increase with every new seam and the final results will be disappointing.</p>
<p><strong>In corset-making, all these defects start popping up during the very last work stages. </strong>Corset garments will not let you get away with “Uh, it will do!”</p>
<p><strong>Sewing mock-ups is really worth it because you can eliminate all defects and errors which may arise during the calculation of adjustments. </strong></p>
<p><strong>- Double-check the lengths of the corset and the top with great accuracy.</strong></p>
<p><strong>If we stick with the initial picture, we can see that the top was put over the corset before they attached the skirt. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2040.files/image112.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>In other words, the top is joined with the corset. Mock-up corset and top </strong>will allow you to practice joining the two garments together. And after carefully aligning their waistlines, you can even out the bottom edge and give it the desired shape: V-shape, A-shape, etc.</p>

</div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody -->
